3. Difference between Date and Calendar.
-->
| Date                             | Calendar                  |
| -------------------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Represents date and time         | Manipulates date and time |
| Mostly immutable in practice     | Mutable                   |
| Few methods                      | Many methods              |
| Cannot easily add/subtract dates | Can add/subtract dates    |
| Legacy class                     | Improved legacy API       |

Example  
      Calendar cal = Calendar.getInstance();
      
      cal.add(Calendar.DATE, 5);
      
      System.out.println(cal.getTime());







4. How to convert Date to LocalDate or LocalDateTime?
-->Date → LocalDate
            import java.util.Date;
            import java.time.LocalDate;
            import java.time.ZoneId;
            
            public class Demo {
            
                public static void main(String[] args) {
            
                    Date date = new Date();
            
                    LocalDate localDate = date.toInstant()
                                              .atZone(ZoneId.systemDefault())
                                              .toLocalDate();
            
                    System.out.println(localDate);
                }
            }
Date → LocalDateTime
          import java.util.Date;
          import java.time.LocalDateTime;
          import java.time.ZoneId;
          
          public class Demo {
          
              public static void main(String[] args) {
          
                  Date date = new Date();
          
                  LocalDateTime ldt = date.toInstant()
                                          .atZone(ZoneId.systemDefault())
                                          .toLocalDateTime();
          
                  System.out.println(ldt);
              }
          }





5. How do you format a Date using SimpleDateFormat with a custom pattern?
-->SimpleDateFormat formats dates into a desired string format.

Example

import java.util.Date;
import java.text.SimpleDateFormat;

public class Demo {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Date date = new Date();

        SimpleDateFormat sdf = new SimpleDateFormat("dd-MM-yyyy");

        System.out.println(sdf.format(date));
    }
}

Output

22-07-2026


| Pattern | Meaning | Example |
| ------- | ------- | ------- |
| dd      | Day     | 22      |
| MM      | Month   | 07      |
| yyyy    | Year    | 2026    |
| HH      | 24-hour | 16      |
| hh      | 12-hour | 04      |
| mm      | Minutes | 45      |
| ss      | Seconds | 20      |
| a       | AM/PM   | PM      |



Example

SimpleDateFormat sdf =
new SimpleDateFormat("dd/MM/yyyy HH:mm:ss");

System.out.println(sdf.format(new Date()));

Output

22/07/2026 16:45:20





6. Why is the Date class considered legacy?
-->Date is considered a legacy class because Java introduced the modern java.time API in Java 8, which is more powerful and easier to use.

Limitations of Date
Many methods are deprecated.
Mutable (can be modified).
Not thread-safe.
Poor API design.
Difficult date calculations.
Time zone handling is limited.
Modern Alternative

Use the java.time package:

LocalDate
LocalTime
LocalDateTime
ZonedDateTime
Instant
Interview Answer

java.util.Date is considered a legacy class because it has deprecated methods, is mutable, not thread-safe, and provides 
limited functionality. Since Java 8, the java.time package is the recommended API for handling dates and times due to its 
immutability, thread safety, and rich set of features.
